    takeaway: "Full fine-tuning is a non-starter for a multi-tenant customization service — it needs ~4× model memory to train and produces a full 140GB copy *per customer*. LoRA/PEFT freezes the base and trains a tiny (~50–300MB) low-rank adapter (rank/alpha/target-modules; QLoRA fits a 70B tune on one GPU). The productization unlock is multi-adapter serving: one base loaded once plus many swappable adapters, with batched multi-LoRA inference (S-LoRA/Punica) so N customers are served from roughly one model's GPU. Treat adapters as first-class artifacts — version, A/B, hot-swap per tenant, roll back instantly by re-pointing the router; keep them separate (merge only for single-tenant latency). And know LoRA's ceiling: behavioral customization yes, a genuinely new domain/language needs full FT or continued pretraining.",
    scenario: "Now let's put this to work. You're building a fine-tuning-*as-a-service* product: 50 enterprise customers, each wanting a model tuned on *their* data and voice. An engineer proposes the naive plan — full fine-tune a separate 70B per customer.\n\nTake a moment: why does this break, and what's the right architecture? Here's the reasoning, step by step. Full fine-tuning produces a *complete* model copy per customer. At ~140GB each in fp16, 50 customers means 50 × 140GB = 7TB of weights, plus 50 separate GPU deployments sitting mostly idle — the unit economics never close. Now apply the low-rank insight: freeze one shared base, and train a tiny (~50–300MB) LoRA adapter per customer. Fifty adapters at ~150MB is ~7.5GB — a rounding error next to a single 140GB base. So instead of 50 full deployments you load the base *once* and keep the adapters in memory. The final piece is serving: batched multi-LoRA systems like S-LoRA and Punica batch requests from *different* customers together, apply each request's adapter via specialized kernels, and share the base-model compute across the whole batch — so 50 customers are served from roughly one model's worth of GPU at high utilization. That collapse from 7TB-and-impossible to one-base-plus-swappable-adapters is exactly the productization the interviewer is probing for.",
